<BaseLayout title="About — VialLogic Learn">
  <section class="max-w-[var(--container-prose)] mx-auto px-6 pt-16 pb-20">
    <div class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-cyan font-bold mb-3">About the course</div>
    <h1 class="text-[2.5rem] font-bold tracking-[-0.035em] leading-[1.05] mb-8 text-text">What you'll actually learn here.</h1>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>Most peptide content stops at "this compound reduced inflammation." That's not knowledge — it's a label. <strong>VialLogic Learn</strong> is built on the premise that real understanding requires going deeper: <em>how</em> the inflammation is reduced, <em>which</em> signaling pathways are touched, <em>where</em> in the body, <em>for how long</em>, and <em>what else</em> the molecule may be doing along the way.</p>

      <h2>The curriculum approach</h2>
      <p>The course is organized in two phases. The <strong>Foundations</strong> modules teach the pharmacology and biology vocabulary every peptide discussion uses — receptors, half-lives, signaling cascades, routes of administration, and how to read research critically. Without this foundation, deep-dive modules become memorization. With it, every compound makes sense as a variation on principles you already understand.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Deep Dive</strong> modules then cover individual compounds at expert depth: discovery, structure, mechanisms (every signaling pathway, not a one-line summary), tissue specificity, pharmacokinetics, tolerance, synergies, and — critically — open questions and limitations. Each module ends with a self-test against the actual standard: <em>can you discuss this compound with someone who studies it?</em></p>

      <h2>How it's designed to teach</h2>
      <p>The format isn't accidental. Three principles drive every module:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Layered depth.</strong> Each section starts with the core idea, then expands. Stop reading at any layer and you still gained real understanding.</li>
        <li><strong>Active recall checkpoints.</strong> Questions throughout each module force you to reconstruct what you just read. This is how learning becomes durable.</li>
        <li><strong>Connections, not lists.</strong> Modules reference each other so the curriculum becomes a web of related concepts, not a stack of isolated facts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What this is, and isn't</h2>
      <p>This is <strong>not</strong> medical advice. It's not a protocol guide, dosing recommendation, or endorsement of peptide use. It's an education on how this class of molecules works at the biological level — knowledge that applies whether you're a researcher, a clinician, a journalist, or simply someone who refuses to be talked down to about a topic that matters to you.</p>

      <p>The companion calculator at <a href="https://www.viallogic.com">viallogic.com</a> handles the practical side of reconstitution math. The course handles the science.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
